description.en: An ontology designed to support semantic-based explicit knowledge management for web development projects. WDO provides a structured vocabulary for representing artifacts like codebase components (classes, functions, attributes), documentation, licensing information, READMEs, best practices, and various digital assets extracted from local repositories or github oranizations. Its goal is to simplify the management, retrieval, and understanding of explicit knowledge within web development projects.

comments.en: Web Development Ontology (WDO) is aligned with Basic Formal Ontology (BFO) 2020 (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/bfo/2020/bfo-core.owl) as its top-level ontology and adapts concepts from DoCO and CodeOntology where relevant to the web development domain.

publisher.value: Department of Computer Science, Addis Ababa University

definition.value: A Statically Typed Language Code is a Programming Language Code written in a language where variable types are checked at compile-time. This is an abstract class.
A GraphQL Code is a Query Language Code that is a query or schema written in the GraphQL language.
A Commit is a process that records a snapshot of changes to one or more files in a repository at a specific time.

example.value: The Git process initiated by `git commit` which creates a new point in the project history.

definition.value: A Software Framework is an Information Content Entity that provides a reusable, generic platform of code for software applications, so that developers can focus on the specific logic of their application. This is an abstract class.
A JSON is a Data Format that structures data according to the JavaScript Object Notation syntax.
A Textual Element is an Information Content Entity which is a discrete piece of text forming part of a larger document structure. This is an abstract class.

example.value: The content of a heading 'Setup Instructions'; the text of a single sentence within a paragraph.

definition.value: A List is a Textual Element which consists of a series of items arranged in a sequence.

example.value: An unordered list of features in a README file; an ordered list of installation steps.

definition.value: A Programming Language Code is a type of Software Code written in a language with formal syntax, typically used to implement application logic. This is an abstract class.
A Build File is a Digital Information Carrier that bears a Build Script.

example.value: A file named 'pom.xml' (Maven), 'build.gradle' (Gradle), or 'Makefile'.

definition.value: An Import Declaration is a Code Construct that is a statement making entities from another module or package available for use.

example.value: The statement `import React from 'react';` in JavaScript or `from collections import Counter` in Python.

definition.value: An Image Description is a Digital Asset Description that defines the characteristics of a raster or vector image, such as its dimensions and format.
A Class Definition is a Complex Type which is the specification of a class, defining a template for objects with data attributes and methods.

example.value: The complete source code defining the 'OrderProcessor' class.

definition.value: An Enum Definition is a Complex Type that defines an enumeration, a special data type consisting of a set of named constants.

example.value: The definition `enum Status { PENDING, PROCESSING, COMPLETED }` in Java or TypeScript.

definition.value: A Repository is an Object Aggregate whose parts are a collection of digital information carriers (files) and their revision history, managed by a version control system.

example.value: A local or remote Git repository for a web application project.

definition.value: A Three-Dimensional Model Description is a Digital Asset Description that defines the characteristics of a 3D model, such as its geometry and textures.
A License File is a Digital Information Carrier that primarily bears a License.

example.value: A file named 'LICENSE.txt' containing the MIT license text.

definition.value: A Document Section is a Textual Element whose role is to group a set of thematically related textual elements within a larger document.

example.value: The 'API Endpoints' section in a technical specification document.

definition.value: A Dockerfile Specification is an Information Content Entity that is a set of instructions for building a Docker container image.

example.value: The sequence of commands like `FROM`, `RUN`, and `COPY` inside a Dockerfile.

definition.value: An XML is a Data Format that structures data according to the Extensible Markup Language syntax.
A JavaScript Code is an Interpreted Language Code written in the JavaScript programming language.
A Notebook is an Information Content Entity which represents the structured content of a computational notebook, including code cells, documentation, and outputs. This is an abstract class.
A Module is a Software Package which is a self-contained unit of code (often corresponding to a single file) that encapsulates related functionality and can be imported for reuse.

example.value: A Python file (`utils.py`) or a JavaScript file (`api.js`) that exports functions or classes.

definition.value: A Variable Declaration is a Code Construct which is the declaration of a variable within a local scope, such as a function body.

example.value: The declaration `let counter = 0;` inside a JavaScript function.

definition.value: A Paragraph is a Textual Element which is a self-contained unit of discourse dealing with a particular point or idea.

example.value: A block of text in a README file explaining a specific feature.

definition.value: A Video Description is a Digital Asset Description that defines the characteristics of a video, such as its duration, frame rate, and encoding.
A Contribution Guide is a type of Guide that explains how to contribute to a project.

example.value: A CONTRIBUTING.md file outlining the process for submitting pull requests.

definition.value: A Data Format is an Information Content Entity that defines the structure and syntax for serializing data for storage or transmission. This is an abstract class.
A Ruby Code is an Interpreted Language Code written in the Ruby programming language.
An SQL Code is a Query Language Code that is a query or schema written in the Structured Query Language (SQL).
A Code Comment is a type of Documentation which is embedded within source code to explain parts of the code.

example.value: A Javadoc block above a method; an inline comment like '// Temporary fix for bug #123'.

definition.value: A CSS Framework is a Software Framework that provides a collection of pre-written CSS files and other assets to facilitate web design.

example.value: Bootstrap, Foundation, Tailwind CSS.

definition.value: A Build Script is an Information Content Entity that specifies the instructions, tasks, and dependencies for a build system to compile, test, and package a software project.

example.value: The XML content of a pom.xml file defining project dependencies; the Groovy script within a build.gradle file.

definition.value: A Template is a type of Markup which defines a pre-formatted structure that can be filled with data to produce a final document.

example.value: A Handlebars (.hbs) or EJS (.ejs) file containing placeholders for dynamic data.

definition.value: A Documentation File is a Digital Information Carrier that primarily bears Documentation.

example.value: A 'CONTRIBUTING.md' Markdown file; a 'user_guide.docx' Word document; a 'README.md' file.

definition.value: An Architectural Decision Record is a type of Documentation that captures an important architectural decision made along with its context and consequences.
Documentation is an Information Content Entity that provides explanatory or reference information about a system, software, or process. This is an abstract class.

example.value: The content of a user manual; API documentation generated by Javadoc; inline code comments.

definition.value: An Organization is an Object Aggregate whose parts are people and assets, which acts as a social or legal agent to manage projects and own repositories.

example.value: A software company like 'Thinkster', the 'Apache Software Foundation', or a university department.

definition.value: A Query Language Code is a Programming Language Code written in a language used to make queries in databases and information systems. This is an abstract class.
A C# Code is a Statically Typed Language Code written in the C# programming language.
An Issue is an Information Content Entity that describes a unit of work to be done, such as a bug, task, or enhancement request in a project.

example.value: A bug report titled "User cannot log in with valid credentials" in a Jira or GitHub issue tracker.

definition.value: A Web Development Project is a process that encompasses all activities involved in creating, deploying, or maintaining a web-based software system.

example.value: The 'Apollo E-commerce Platform Upgrade' project aiming to refactor the checkout module over three months.

definition.value: A License is an Information Content Entity that specifies the terms and conditions for software use, modification, and distribution.

example.value: The full text of the MIT License; the specific clauses of the Apache License 2.0.

definition.value: A CSS Code is a Stylesheet written in the Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) language.
A Notebook File is a Digital Information Carrier that bears Notebook content.

example.value: A file named `data_analysis.ipynb`.

definition.value: A Function Call Site is a Code Construct that represents a single, specific invocation of a function or method.

example.value: The specific code `calculatePrice(item, 10)` in a line of a script.

definition.value: A Test Code is a type of Software Code whose purpose is to verify the correctness of other software code.

example.value: A unit test written using JUnit or PyTest; an integration test script.

definition.value: A Jupyter Notebook is a type of Notebook that conforms to the .ipynb format structure, containing a list of cells with code, text, and output.

example.value: The JSON content of an .ipynb file describing a sequence of executable Python code and Markdown cells for data analysis.

definition.value: A Code Block is a Textual Element which consists of a formatted block of example source code within a document.

example.value: A snippet of Python code demonstrating API usage, enclosed in triple backticks in a Markdown file.

definition.value: A Web Presentation Code is a type of Software Code that defines the structure, layout, and styling of a user interface for the web. This is an abstract class.
A Guide is a type of Documentation that provides instructions on how to use, set up, or contribute to a project. This is an abstract class.
A Configuration File is a Digital Information Carrier that bears one or more Configuration Settings.

example.value: A '.env' file storing environment variables; a 'webpack.config.js' file; a 'settings.json' file.

definition.value: An Information Content Entity is a generically dependent continuant that is dependent on some information bearer for its concretization and is about some entity. This is an abstract class.

example.value: The textual content of a specific license agreement; the set of instructions defining a particular JavaScript function; the design description for a company logo.

definition.value: A Python Code is an Interpreted Language Code written in the Python programming language.
A User Interface Design Description is a Digital Asset Description that defines the visual layout and interactive elements of a user interface, such as a wireframe or mockup.
A YAML is a Data Format that structures data according to the YAML Ain't Markup Language syntax.
A Type is a Code Construct which represents the specification of a data type in a programming language. This is an abstract class.
A Table is a Textual Element which consists of data arranged in rows and columns.

example.value: A table comparing feature plans in documentation, often created with pipe characters (`|`) in Markdown.

definition.value: A Best Practice Guideline is a type of Documentation that describes recommended methods or techniques for development.

example.value: A document outlining 'Secure Coding Practices'; a style guide for writing maintainable CSS.

definition.value: A TypeScript Code is a Statically Typed Language Code written in the TypeScript programming language.
A Source Code File is a Digital Information Carrier that primarily bears Software Code. This is an abstract class.

example.value: The file 'server.js' containing JavaScript code; 'models.py' containing Python classes; 'database_schema.sql' containing SQL DDL statements.

definition.value: A Stylesheet File is a Digital Information Carrier that bears a Stylesheet.

example.value: A file named `styles.css` or `theme.scss`.

definition.value: A Log File is a Digital Information Carrier that bears Log information.

example.value: A file named `application.log` or `access.log`.

definition.value: An Attribute Declaration is a Code Construct which is the declaration of a field, attribute, or property within a class, struct, or interface.

example.value: The declaration 'private String username;' within a Java class; 'const API_KEY = "..."' in a JavaScript module.

definition.value: A Java Code is a Statically Typed Language Code written in the Java programming language.
A Heading is a Textual Element which is the title that introduces a section of a document.

example.value: The content of a markdown heading `## Installation`.

definition.value: A JavaScript Framework is a Software Framework written in JavaScript that provides structure for building web applications.

example.value: React, Angular, Vue.js.

definition.value: A User Guide is a type of Guide that explains how to use a software product from an end-user perspective.
A Rust Code is a Statically Typed Language Code written in the Rust programming language.
A Software Package is an Information Content Entity which represents a distributable unit of reusable code, such as a library or module. This is an abstract class.

example.value: The 'requests' package in Python; the 'lodash' package in NPM.

definition.value: A Markup File is a Digital Information Carrier that bears Markup code.

example.value: A file named `index.html`, `main.jsx`, or `document.xml`.

definition.value: A Function Definition is a Code Construct which is the specification of a function, method, or constructor, including its signature and body.

example.value: The source code for a 'getUserById(userId)' method; the definition of a 'Product()' constructor.

definition.value: A Dockerfile is a Digital Information Carrier that bears a Dockerfile Specification.

example.value: A text file named 'Dockerfile' used to build a container image.

definition.value: A Digital Information Carrier is a generically dependent continuant that is a digital object, typically a file, which serves to encode or bear an Information Content Entity. This is an abstract class.

example.value: A specific file named 'styles.css'; an image file 'logo.png'; a document 'API_Guide.pdf'.

definition.value: An Asset File is a Digital Information Carrier that bears the content of a non-code, non-documentation digital resource, such as an image, video, or font. This is an abstract class.

example.value: An image file 'hero-banner.jpg'; an audio file 'notification.mp3'; a font file 'Roboto-Regular.ttf'.

definition.value: A Configuration Setting is an Information Content Entity that is a parameter or setting used to control the behavior of a software application or system.

example.value: The content of a 'database_url = ...' setting in a .env file; a JSON object defining feature flags.

definition.value: A Trait Definition is a Complex Type that defines a collection of methods that can be implemented by other types, used for sharing functionality between classes.

example.value: The definition `trait Loggable { fn log(&self); }` in Rust.

definition.value: A Blockquote is a Textual Element which consists of a block of quoted text.

example.value: A customer testimonial quoted in a README file, often prefixed with '>' in Markdown.

definition.value: A Go Code is a Statically Typed Language Code written in the Go programming language.

An Argument is a CodeConstruct representing the use of a value (variable, attribute, or literal) as an argument at a specific function callsite. It may refer to a VariableDeclaration, AttributeDeclaration, or be a literal value.
An HTML Code is a Markup written in the HyperText Markup Language (HTML).
A Parameter is a Code Construct which is the specification of a variable bound within the scope of a function or method signature.

example.value: The 'int count' parameter in a function signature 'void printItems(int count)'.

definition.value: An API Documentation is a type of Documentation that describes an Application Programming Interface (API), including its endpoints, methods, parameters, and return values.

example.value: A specification generated by Swagger/OpenAPI; documentation for a REST or GraphQL API.

definition.value: A Primitive Type is a Type which represents a basic data type provided by a programming language, such as an integer, boolean, or string.

example.value: The 'boolean' type in Python; the 'int' type specification in C++.

definition.value: A Commit Message is an Information Content Entity that is a textual description of the changes made in a specific commit process.

example.value: "feat: Add user authentication endpoint" or "fix: Correct calculation error in shopping cart (closes #241)".

definition.value: A Font Description is a Digital Asset Description that defines the characteristics of a font, such as its family name and style.

A Container Image is a Digital Information Carrier that bears a specification for creating a runnable software container, which is a standalone, executable package including all necessary code, runtime, and tools.

example.value: A Docker image such as 'nginx:latest' or a custom-built image like 'my-app:1.2.0'.

definition.value: An Audio Description is a Digital Asset Description that represents the informational nature of an audio recording, such as its duration, sample rate, and encoding.
A PHP Code is an Interpreted Language Code written in the PHP programming language.
A Changelog is a type of Documentation that consists of a chronologically ordered list of notable changes made to a project.
An Interpreted Language Code is a Programming Language Code written in a language that is executed by an interpreter without prior compilation. This is an abstract class.
A Stylesheet is a type of Web Presentation Code which defines the presentation and styling rules for a markup document. This is an abstract class.

example.value: A CSS file defining colors, fonts, and layout; an SASS or LESS file.

definition.value: A Software Code is an Information Content Entity which is a set of instructions or declarations written in a formal language, intended to be processed by a computer. This is an abstract class.

example.value: A 'User.java' class definition; the algorithm in a 'calculatePrice' function; declarations in a CSS stylesheet.

definition.value: A Readme is a type of Documentation that provides essential information about a software project, typically serving as the entry point for a repository.

example.value: The textual content and structure within a 'README.md' file, including sections like 'Installation' and 'Usage'.

definition.value: A Complex Type is a Type which represents a composite data type, such as a class, interface, or enumeration. This is an abstract class.
An Archive File is a Digital Information Carrier that packages and optionally compresses one or more other files into a single file.

example.value: A file named 'project.zip', 'backup.tar.gz', 'library.jar', or 'archive.7z'.

definition.value: A Tutorial is a type of Guide that provides step-by-step instructions to complete a specific task.
An Interface Definition is a Complex Type which is the specification of an abstract type used to define a contract of methods that a class must implement.

example.value: The content defining the 'Serializable' interface in Java.

definition.value: A Markup is a type of Web Presentation Code that defines the structure and semantics of a document using a system of tags. This is an abstract class.

example.value: An HTML document defining headings, paragraphs, and links.

definition.value: A Database Schema is a form of SQL Code which defines the structure, tables, columns, and relationships of a database using Data Definition Language (DDL) statements.

example.value: The content of a .sql file containing `CREATE TABLE` statements.

definition.value: A Struct Definition is a Complex Type that defines a struct, a composite data type that groups variables under a single name.

example.value: The definition `struct Point { int x; int y; }` in C or Go.

definition.value: A Code Construct is a type of Software Code that represents a syntactically atomic unit of a programming language, such as a type, a function definition, or a declaration. This is an abstract class.
A Log is an Information Content Entity that is a record of events that occurred while a software application was running.

example.value: A textual entry like '2025-07-06 12:00:00, ERROR: Database connection failed'.

definition.value: A person who has contributed to a project or repository in any capacity, including but not limited to code, documentation, design, or support.
A Digital Asset Description is an Information Content Entity that defines the characteristics, design, or descriptive metadata for a digital asset. This is an abstract class.

example.value: A description for a banner image including its required dimensions; metadata describing an audio clip's purpose.

definition.value: A relation indicating that a software code content entity contains a code construct as one of its parts.
A data property that specifies the width of the image in pixels.
A relation from a code construct to the larger code entity that declares it.
A relation from an Argument node at a callsite to the VariableDeclaration it refers to as an argument value.
A specific relation from a function to the call site that invokes it.
A relation between a digital information carrier (e.g., a file) and the information content entity it encodes or represents.
A relation linking a repository or project to a person who has contributed to it in any capacity.
A relation between a file and the commit process that changed it.
A data property that specifies the name of the programming language (e.g., "Java", "Python").
A relation from an architectural choice to the decision record that justifies it.
A relation linking a person to the commits they have performed as committer.
A relation linking a repository to the commits in its history.
A relation that links a repository to the project or organization it belongs to.
A relation from a source code file to the build script that compiles it.
A relation from a code construct to the function call site where it is used as an argument.
A data property that specifies the common name of the image format (e.g., "JPEG", "PNG", "SVG").
A relation from a FunctionDefinition to the VariableDeclaration entities that are declared as local variables within its scope.

example.value: A JavaScript function `calculateTotal()` that declares variables like `let subtotal = 0;` and `let tax = 0.1;` would have `hasLocalVariable` relationships to those variable declarations.

definition.value: A data property that indicates whether a digital information carrier was removed (deleted or moved) in a commit.
A data property that specifies the unique identifier for an issue from its tracking system (e.g., "PROJ-123").
A relation indicating that an entity (e.g., SoftwareCode, a process) adheres to a BestPracticeGuideline.
A relation from an entity to the documentation that describes it.
A relation from a type to the function definition that returns it.
A data property that specifies the encoding format of a media asset (e.g., "H.264" for video, "AAC" for audio).
A relation from an HTML entity to the programming language code that manipulates it.
A specific relation between a single FunctionCallSite and the FunctionDefinition it invokes.
A relation linking a commit to the person who performed the commit operation (committer in Git).
A data property that specifies whether a class cannot be subclassed or a field cannot be reassigned.
A relation linking a repository to the digital information carriers (files) it contains.
A relation indicating that a piece of software code is built upon or makes use of a software framework.
A relation from a build script to the final distributable archive artifact it creates (e.g., a JAR, ZIP, wheel).
An abstract relation indicating that one function is called by another function's logic.
A relation from an attribute declaration to the complex type that declares it as a field.
A relation that links an Architectural Decision Record to the architectural component or design choice it justifies.
A data property that specifies the simple, unqualified name of an information content entity.
A relation from a type to the code construct that has that type.
A relation between a Complex Type (Class, Interface, Trait) and a FunctionDefinition that it declares as a method.
A data property that specifies the file extension of a digital information carrier (e.g., 'py', 'md', 'png').
A relation from a smaller document part to the larger document that contains it.
A relation between a Complex Type and an AttributeDeclaration that it declares as a field.
A data property that specifies the date and time when a commit was created or recorded in the repository.
A data property that specifies the size of a file in bytes.
A relation between test code and the application code it is intended to verify.
A relation that is the inverse of 'tests', indicating that a piece of software code is verified by a set of test code.
A relation from an issue to a commit that makes progress on it.
A relation from a piece of software code to the template it is embedded in.
A relation linking a commit to the repository it belongs to.
A data property that specifies the sample rate of an audio asset in Hertz (Hz).
A data property that specifies the ending line number of an information entity within its source file.
A data property that specifies the timestamp when a file was last modified.
A data property that specifies whether a function is asynchronous, meaning it may not complete its execution immediately.
A relation from a container image to the Dockerfile specification that is based on it.
The inverse relation, linking a VariableDeclaration to Argument nodes that refer to it as an argument at a callsite.
A relation from a package to the build script or other package that depends on it.
A relation from a build script to the source code files it processes during compilation.
A data property that specifies the path of a file relative to the root of its source repository.
A data property that specifies the URL path for an API endpoint (e.g., "/api/users/{id}").
A data property that specifies the visibility of a field or method (e.g., "public", "private", "protected").
A data property that specifies the quantitative measure of the number of linearly independent paths through a function's source code.
A relation indicating that a Complex Type is a superclass or supertype for another Complex Type.
A relation indicating that a ClassDefinition implements an InterfaceDefinition, TraitDefinition, or StructDefinition.
A data property that specifies the fully qualified or canonical name of a code element (e.g., package.class.method).
A relation from a VariableDeclaration to the FunctionDefinition that declares it as a local variable within its scope.

example.value: A variable declaration `let counter = 0;` inside a JavaScript function `calculateTotal()` would have `isLocalVariableOf` pointing to that function.

definition.value: A relation indicating that a function or method reads from or writes to a variable, attribute, or field.
A relation from a framework to the software code that is built upon it.
A specific relation indicating that a documentation element, such as a code comment, is about a code entity.
A data property that specifies the frame rate of a video asset in frames per second.
A relation indicating that a module uses or includes another module to access its functionality.
A relation from a Dockerfile specification to the base container image it extends.
A data property that specifies the version string of a software package or framework (e.g., "16.8.0", "5.2.3").
A data property that holds the literal content of an information entity, such as a configuration setting or commit message.
A relation from a distributable archive file to the build script that created it.
A relation from an output or deliverable to the WebDevelopmentProject that produced it.
A relation between a WebDevelopmentProject (a process) and an InformationContentEntity that is its output or deliverable.
A data property that holds the literal source code string of a code construct.
A relation linking a Commit process to its descriptive CommitMessage entity.
A relation from an interface, trait, or struct to a class that implements it.
A data property that specifies the family name of a font (e.g., "Arial", "Times New Roman").
A data property that specifies the standard identifier for a license, preferably its SPDX ID (e.g., "MIT", "Apache-2.0").
An abstract relation indicating that one function's logic calls another function. This can be inferred from 'callsFunction'.
A data property that specifies the hierarchical level of a heading in a document (e.g., 1 for h1, 2 for h2).
A specific relation from a code entity to the documentation that is about it.
A data property that specifies the style of a font (e.g., "Regular", "Italic", "Bold").
A relation linking a CommitMessage to the Commit process it describes.
A relation linking a file to the repository that contains it.
A data property that specifies the number of lexical tokens in a piece of code.
A relation indicating that a build script or software package specifies another package as a dependency.
A relation between a FunctionDefinition and a Parameter that it declares.
A relation between a FunctionCallSite and a CodeConstruct (such as a VariableDeclaration or a literal value) passed as an argument.
A relation indicating that a template contains embedded software code that is processed at runtime.
A relation that is the inverse of 'bearerOfInformation', linking an information entity to the digital carrier that encodes it.
A relation from a function definition to the complex type that declares it as a method.
A general relation indicating that a code entity (like a class or module) declares a smaller code construct (like a method or attribute) as one of its parts.
A relation between a commit process and the file(s) it changed.
A data property that specifies the duration of a time-based media asset, such as video or audio, represented as a decimal number of total seconds.
A data property that specifies the URL of the remote repository.
A relation that links a commit to an issue it makes progress on or is related to.
A data property that specifies the starting line number of an information entity within its source file.
A transitive part-whole relation between an InformationContentEntity (like a document) and a smaller InformationContentEntity that is one of its components (like a section or paragraph).
A relation from a declaration to a code construct where that declaration is used.
A relation specifying the Type that a FunctionDefinition returns.
A relation indicating that a code construct is part of a software code content entity.
A relation specifying the Type of a typed code construct (e.g., an attribute, a parameter, a variable).
A relation indicating that a CSS entity provides presentation rules for an HTML entity.
A data property that specifies the allowed HTTP method for an API endpoint (e.g., "GET", "POST").
A data property that holds the literal text value of a textual document component.
A relation from an HTML entity to the CSS entity that styles it.
A relation between a Documentation entity and the entity it describes or explains.
A data property that specifies the number of lines in a piece of code.
A data property that specifies whether a member belongs to the type itself rather than to an instance of that type.
A relation linking the usage of a variable or type in an expression to its original declaration construct.
A relation from an attribute or variable to the function that accesses it.
A relation that is the inverse of 'imports', indicating that a module's functionality is used by another module.
A relation from a parameter to the function definition that declares it.
A relation that links a project or organization to its source code repository.
A data property that specifies the height of the image in pixels.
A relation from a guideline to an entity that conforms to it.
A relation indicating that programming language code acts on or modifies HTML code, such as through the Document Object Model (DOM).
A data property that specifies the unique SHA hash identifying a commit process.
A data property that specifies the current state of an issue (e.g., "Open", "In Progress", "Resolved").
A relation indicating that a Complex Type inherits from or extends another Complex Type.
A data property that specifies the timestamp when a file was first created.
A relation linking a person to a repository or project they have contributed to in any capacity.
